Differential diagnoses: 3-5. Consider: Acute appendicitis (but recurrent, no). Crohn disease (IBD). Hidradenitis? Not. Consider: Meckel's diverticulitis? Not. More appropriate: PFAPA syndrome, but age older. Consider: Hereditary autoinflammatory syndromes like TRAPS, Hyper-IgD syndrome (Mevalonate kinase deficiency), Behçet disease, inflammatory bowel disease, seronegative spondyloarthropathy. Also consider: Peritonitis due to Yersinia, but sterile fluid. So differential: 1) Acute intermittent porphyria (abdominal pain, neuro). 2) Inflammatory bowel disease (Crohn's). 3) Recurrent peritonitis due to bacterial (but sterile). 4) TRAPS (TNF receptor associated periodic syndrome). 5) Behçet disease (though mucocutaneous lesions missing). Provide confidence for each.

Key findings list.

Tests: Genetic testing for MEFV mutations (high priority). Serum amyloid A already elevated. Others: Acute phase reactants during attack (already). Also: Urinalysis for proteinuria (already). Also: Kidney function, amyloidosis screening (urine protein, renal ultrasound). Also: Echocardiogram for pericardial involvement. Also: Rule out other autoinflammatory: TNFRSF1A gene for TRAPS. So tests list: MEFV genetic testing (immediate). Serum amyloid A trending (routine). Kidney function, urine protein quantification (routine). Echocardiogram (routine). Others: Colonoscopy already done.

Management: Immediate: start colchicine (standard). Dose: 0.5 mg to 1 mg twice daily (adjust). For adult male, 1-2 mg daily. Provide specific. Also NSAIDs for pain. Consider IL-1 inhibitors (anakinra, canakinumab) if colchicine resistant/intolerant. Provide steroid taper.

Consultations: Rheumatology (urgent), Genetics (routine), Nephrology (if proteinuria persists). Also Gastroenterology (optional). Provide.

Red flags: Development of AA amyloidosis (renal failure), persistent proteinuria, unexplained weight loss, pericardial effusion leading to tamponade, severe abdominal pain with signs of peritonitis, refractory fever.

